# Single-Language UI Toggle Standard

- Do not display Arabic and English simultaneously in the same visible UI label.
- The interface must render one language at a time based on the active language toggle.
- This rule has higher UI-rendering priority than mixed bilingual labels in legacy screens.
- If there is any conflict, final rendered UI must stay single-language (Arabic-only or English-only).
- When language is Arabic:
  - Show Arabic-only labels, headings, buttons, placeholders, table headers, and hints.
  - Keep RTL direction.
- When language is English:
  - Show English-only labels, headings, buttons, placeholders, table headers, and hints.
  - Switch layout direction to LTR where applicable.
- For any new bilingual UI text added in code:
  - Store both variants using `data-ar` and `data-en` when practical.
  - Or use a predictable bilingual source string that can be split by the language-localization helper.
- All future pages/workspaces must use the same toggle behavior and must be compatible with global language switching.
- Avoid introducing fixed mixed labels like `Arabic / English` in the final rendered UI.
- For dynamic content generated by JavaScript (tables, modals, alerts, print headers):
  - Build strings with language-aware helpers (`t(...)`) or `data-ar` / `data-en`.
  - Do not concatenate bilingual strings in one runtime message.
